        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1538-4727-1901" data-comment-wp-id="1901"  parent-id="blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1538-4727-1896" class="comment level1 collapsable" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/binra/">
                    <img src="http://a0.twimg.com/profile_images/209047734/IMG_6983face_normal.gif" alt="Brian Steere" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/binra/">
                    Brian Steere
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">11 months ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Consciousness focuses attention in specific ways. When it is focussed in the physical senses, you operate as a particular construct of identity. When focussed in the non-physical you are active in ways that your so called waking consciousness denies access or exposure to.<br /> Slumbering, in the sense that you quote, is of unawareness amidst the current event. Mindless distraction amidst skimming the surface of a ‘taken-for-granted’ sleepwalk through life is the slumber of the living dead!<br /> Conscious rest need not become unconscious, simply because of yielding into a deeper sense of the presence and quality of existence itself. Indeed it is the Wellspring from which all comes forth.<br /> Sleep is a clear sign that the source of life in all consciousness of existence is not physical.<br /> Lazy fools may attempt to sleep themselves to health – but there is so much more to sleep than the sleeping can imagine.</p>

    	</div>



